# Performance Safety Rails

You are working in a production Next.js app with performance-sensitive animated sections.
Make minimal, targeted changes only.

## Global rules
- Do NOT refactor unrelated code.
- Do NOT rewrite whole components unless explicitly requested.
- Do NOT change visual behavior unless explicitly requested.
- Do NOT change component public API unless explicitly requested.
- Prefer the smallest safe patch.
- When uncertain, stop and explain instead of improvising.

## Scope control
- Only analyze files explicitly attached with @ in chat.
- Ignore all other files unless the user explicitly expands scope.
- If a fix appears to require more files, first explain why and ask for scope expansion.

## Performance rules
- Never add new polling, intervals, or animation loops unless explicitly requested.
- Never use useState inside high-frequency animation/render loops.
- Prefer useRef for mutable animation state.
- Avoid layout thrashing: do not mix repeated layout reads and writes in the same hot path.
- Avoid unnecessary getBoundingClientRect, offsetHeight, getComputedStyle in scroll/rAF loops.
- Event listeners on scroll/touch/wheel must be passive when possible.
- Video/canvas/WebGL sections must support pause/resume or cleanup when offscreen.
- Do not preload assets unless they are definitely needed early.
- Be suspicious of duplicate player/video SDK loads.
- Do not introduce new third-party scripts unless explicitly requested.

## Workflow rules
- No broad "performance cleanup".
- One hypothesis, one area, one commit.
- First diagnose one issue and propose a minimal patch.
- Apply code changes only after diagnosis and acceptance.

## Required output before code
1. Root cause hypothesis
2. Minimal change plan
3. Files to modify
4. Risks/regressions to watch

## Required output after code
1. What changed
2. Why this should help
3. What should be tested manually

## Forbidden behaviors
- No mass formatting-only diffs.
- No renaming spree.
- No moving files unless explicitly requested.
- No silent behavior changes.
